"Cultural Ethnography of the Sault Ste. Marie Tribe of Chippewa Indians (Baawiting Anishinaabeg)
The Sault Tribe of Chippewa Indians, also known as the Sault Ste. Marie Tribe of Chippewa Indians, is the largest federally recognized tribe in Michigan, with approximately 40,000–44,000 enrolled members. They are part of the broader Anishinaabe (Ojibwe/Chippewa) peoples, whose homelands center on the Great Lakes region. Their traditional territory includes areas around Bawating (Sault Ste. Marie, meaning "The Gathering Place") on the St. Marys River between Lake Superior and Lake Huron.
en.wikipedia.org

This overview draws primarily from the tribe’s official sources and historical context to present a respectful, insider-informed perspective. Traditional ethnography relies on long-term immersion, but here it synthesizes publicly shared cultural knowledge, oral traditions, and contemporary revitalization efforts.

Historical and Geographical Context
The Anishinaabeg have inhabited the Great Lakes Basin for millennia, with archaeological evidence and oral traditions dating back thousands of years. Ancestors of the Sault Tribe were fishing peoples whose settlements dotted the upper Great Lakes. They gathered in larger groups during summers at places like Bawating and dispersed into family units for winter hunting, fishing, and gathering.
saulttribe.com

European contact began in the 1600s with French fur traders, followed by British and American interactions. Key treaties, including the 1820 Treaty of Sault Ste. Marie, the 1836 Treaty of Washington, and the 1855 Treaty, involved land cessions while reserving hunting, fishing, and gathering rights. These rights remain central to tribal identity and legal assertions today.
saulttribe.com

Federal recognition came in 1972 after decades of advocacy by Sugar Island descendants and others. The tribe now operates as a sovereign nation within the U.S., with economic development through Kewadin Casinos funding health, education, housing, and cultural programs.
en.wikipedia.org

Core Cultural Elements: Anishinaabe Bimaadiziwin
Central to Sault Tribe culture is Anishinaabe Bimaadiziwin — the "good life" or "Anishinaabe way of life." This emphasizes harmony with creation, respect for elders and children, reciprocity, and living in balance with the natural world.
saulttribe.com

Language (Anishinaabemowin / Ojibwe): Language is foundational to culture. Revitalization efforts include classes, immersion programs, the Ojibwe Learning Center and Library, and curricula. Much traditional knowledge, stories, and worldview are embedded in the language.
saulttribe.com
Clans (Dodems): Traditional social organization uses clans (e.g., seven original dodems), which dictate roles, responsibilities, and marriage protocols, providing structure and identity.
saulttribe.com
Oral Tradition and Knowledge Transmission: History, morals, and life lessons pass through stories, myths, and teachings from elders. Ceremonies mark life events, seasons, and thanksgiving.
Subsistence and Material Culture: Traditional lifeways centered on fishing (especially whitefish and sturgeon), hunting, wild rice harvesting, maple sugaring, and gathering berries and medicines. Respectful relationships with manidoog (spirits) and the land underpin these practices.

Contemporary Cultural Practices and Revitalization
The tribe actively maintains and revives traditions through dedicated programs:
Language & Culture Division: Includes administration, repatriation/historic preservation (NAGPRA work), Mary Murray Culture Camp, language department, and the Ojibwe Learning Center/Library.
saulttribe.com
Mary Murray Culture Camp: Offers land-based education, traditional skills, feasts, sweat lodges, elder gatherings, and nature activities on Sugar Island.
saulttribe.com
Powwows: Major community events like the Niiwin Noodin Powwow feature grand entries, drumming, dancing, feasting, and vendors. These intertribal gatherings strengthen identity and welcome visitors.
saulttribe.com
Ceremonies: Staff support traditional funerals, feasts, and other rites. Repatriation efforts restore ancestors and sacred items.
Education and Community: The Joseph K. Lumsden Bahweting Anishnaabe Public School Academy integrates language and cultural values. The Chi Mukwa Recreation Center and other facilities support community well-being.
en.wikipedia.org

Worldview and Values
Anishinaabe spirituality emphasizes respect for all creation, interconnectedness, and lifelong learning toward harmony. Ceremonies and daily practices honor spirits (manidoog). Contemporary life navigates sovereignty, economic development, treaty rights, and cultural preservation amid modern challenges like identity, health, and environmental stewardship.
pluralism.org

Ethnographic Reflections
From an ethnographic lens, the Sault Tribe exemplifies resilience and cultural continuity amid colonization, assimilation policies (e.g., boarding schools), and economic marginalization. Contemporary ethnography would highlight hybridity: casino-funded cultural programs, language nests alongside digital resources, and assertions of treaty rights in a globalized world. Community-driven efforts (e.g., culture camps, powwows, and repatriation) reflect agency and the seventh-generation principle — decisions made with future descendants in mind.
